Preheat your oven to 200°C. Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 1cm chunks (no need to peel). Pop the potatoes on a #baking tray{}, drizzle with @oil{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat, spread them out in a single layer. Roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden and crispy, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Meanwhile, halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125%g}. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}. Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a #medium saucepan{} over a medium high heat. When hot, add the sliced onion, garlic, @red wine vinegar{12%ml} and a pinch of @sugar{}. Place a lid on the pan. Cook gently until the onions are really nice and soft, ~{10%minutes}. Add a splash of @water{} to help soften the onions. Stir occasionally, ensuring the onions don't stick to the bottom of the pan.

Put the @cod fillets{2} on a lined baking tray. Season the cod with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Coat the top of the cod with the @dukkah mix{1}. Drizzle the cod with @oil{} and roast on the middle shelf for ~{7-8%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw fish.

> IMPORTANT: The fish is cooked when opaque in the middle.

Next add the halved tomatoes and @samphire{40%g} to the pan with the onion. Cook until they start to soften and break down, ~{3-4%minutes}. Take off the heat and set aside until ready to serve.

Share the potatoes between your plates and top with the roasted cod. Spoon the salsa on the side. Enjoy!